<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: ROSE GETS GOOD REPORTS IN PRISON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Pete Rose is earning 11 cents an hour working in a prison machine shop and 
isn't playing for the inmates' softball team yet, the assistant warden said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Rose, serving a five-month sentence at the Federal Work Camp in Marion, Ill., 
spends eight hours a day welding and fabricating metal with 70 other prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
"His work supervisor says he has been getting good reports; he gets in there 
and works just as hard as the rest of them," assistant warden Randy Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
Baseball's all-time hit leader has also been watching the inmate softball 
teams, but hasn't been able to play because his knee is healing from surgery 
July 20, Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
Davis said Rose is treated like any other inmate -- doing basic chores eight 
hours a day and sharing a dormitory cubicle with another prisoner. Rose is 
scheduled to be released Jan. 7, then spend three months at a halfway house in 
Cincinnati. 
</P>
</TEXT>
