<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: BUENA PARK; 
</P>
<P>
BOYS CLUB DIRECTOR QUITS AFTER PROTESTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LYNDA NATALI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The executive director of the Buena Park Boys Club announced his resignation 
this week, less than a month after angry parents, athletes and children 
protested the dismissal of Bob Eastland, a 30-year employee of the 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
Erik Larson, who was hired 11 months ago to run the club, resigned Wednesday, 
according to John Leland, president of the board of directors. Leland declined 
to provide details about Larson's departure; he said, however, that the recent 
outcry over Eastland's dismissal played a part. 
</P>
<P>
"I feel that there was a lot of misunderstanding as to what we were trying to 
do at the Boys Club," Leland said. "He (Larson) just felt it was best." 
</P>
<P>
Larson could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the board has offered Eastland another position which he has 
accepted. Eastland, acknowledged a popular employee, was given notice in June 
and told that his $40,000-a-year job had been eliminated because of a budget 
crunch. Eventually, he was offered another position at substantially less pay. 
</P>
<P>
Eastland's initial dismissal prompted about 120 protesters to picket the club 
last month. Parents whose children participate in a wheelchair-hockey program 
led the demonstration in an effort to reverse his dismissal. The protesters 
said they were afraid that the program and others run by Eastland also would be 
eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
Eastland said he was thrilled over the recent offer despite a $10,000 pay cut. 
"They are in financial trouble. Maybe as we get going, the salary will go up," 
he said, adding that the board told him he could apply for the executive 
director's job vacated by Larson. 
</P>
<P>
Since the issue over Eastland arose, two members of the board of directors have 
resigned. Trustee Donna Bagley has since returned. Priscilla Atkinson, 
assistant director of the Buena Park Chamber of Commerce, said that new 
obligations with the city's VISION 2010 committee have forced her to leave her 
post. 
</P>
<P>
The club is not expected to fill the executive director's post for several 
months, Leland said. LYNDA NATALI 
</P>
</TEXT>
