<P>
SPILL CLOSES 3 FREEWAY LANES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A chemical spill forced officials to close three lanes of the northbound Golden 
State Freeway near Gorman for more than four hours early this morning, the 
California Highway Patrol reported. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities said a truck rear-ended another truck carrying a shipment of 
antifreeze and other chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
The 3 a.m. accident occurred half a mile south of California 138. Antifreeze 
spilled onto the roadway, but there were no injuries and only minor truck 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles County firefighters called for a hazardous materials unit after 
learning that the truck carried a variety of chemicals that could be dangerous. 
After firefighters determined that only antifreeze leaked, the emergency was 
downgraded and sand was used to soak up the liquid. All freeway lanes were 
reopened by 7:42 a.m., the CHP said. 
</P>
